{"title_page": "Sacha Lord", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Sacha Lord\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Sacha John Edward Lord\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1972|01|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Manchester]], United Kingdom\n| nationality   = British\n| occupation    = {{Hlist|Music entrepreneur|Adviser}}\n| known_for     = {{Unbulleted list|Co-founder of [[The Warehouse Project]]|Co-founder of [[Parklife (festival)]]|Night Time Economy Adviser for [[Greater Manchester]]}}\n| website = {{URL|https://parklife.uk.com|Parklife Festival}}\n}}\n\n'''Sacha John Edward Lord''' (born 26th January 1972) is an English entrepreneur and co-creator of the [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife festival]] and [[The Warehouse Project]]. He is also the Night Time Economy Adviser for [[Greater Manchester]].\n\n== Early life ==\n\nLord was born in [[Altrincham]], Greater Manchester, and grew up in the town. His father was a textile merchant, and his mother an interior designer. Lord was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]], leaving at aged 18 having gained two Us and an E at A-Level.  After leaving school, Lord went on to work at a clothes shop in [[Altrincham]], and later started a market stall at [[Liverpool]] market, selling leather jackets. After quitting his market job, Lord quickly found himself involved in the rave-influenced music scene, and spent most of his time listening to [[The Stone Roses]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[The Smiths]] and [[David Bowie|Bowie]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=squaremile.com|publisher=Square Mile}}</ref>\n\n== The Warehouse Project ==\n\nInspired by the success of the events, Lord launched [[the Warehouse Project]], a series of rave events running annually from September to 1 January, in 2006 with Co-Founder Sam Kandel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enforbusiness.com/interview/five-minutes-sacha-lord-marchionne-and-sam-kandel-founders-warehouse-project|title=Five minutes with... Sacha Lord-Marchionne and Sam Kandel, founders of the Warehouse Project|website=EN For Business|accessdate=1 October 2019}}}</ref>\n\nIt began operations in the disused [[Strangeways Brewery|Boddingtons Brewery]] in [[Strangeways]], and then moved into a space under [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly station]], on Store Street, which previously served as an air raid shelter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djmag.com/news/detail/921|title=The Warehouse Project|website=djmag.com|publisher=DJ Mag}}</ref>\n\nThe opening night of The Warehouse Project was described by Lord as a nightmare due to its location next to the prison, and he later revealed the Governor of [[HM Prison Manchester]] had called to say it was disturbing inmates.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe Warehouse Project went onto feature some of the most in-demand names in international house and techno music, including [[New Order (band)|New Order]], [[The Chemical Brothers]] and [[Calvin Harris]] - whose appearance, Lord later went onto reveal, was a favour for an A&R at Sony. Lord revealed he put Harris ( an unknown DJ at the time) on the 21.30 slot, despite doors only opening at 22.00.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe Warehouse Project attracted 100,000 people in its first year and has continued to sell out annually.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/sacha-lord-warehouse-project-founder-appointed-manchesters-night-time-economy-adviser-future-24-hour-clubbing-2366958#CPOiVsbVBBUvryY5.99|title=Sacha Lord: the Warehouse Project founder and Manchester\u2019s Night Time Economy Adviser on the future of the city\u2019s club scene|website=NME|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Lord and Kandel moved The Warehouse Project to Depot at the former [[Manchester Mayfield railway station]] - a move which saw it become the biggest club night in the UK with a 10,000 person capacity. The move also put it on a par with the current Guinness Book of World Records holder of the largest nightclub in the world, [[Privilege Ibiza|Privilege]] in Ibiza, which can also hold 10,000 revellers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pretty52.com/news/music-the-worlds-biggest-nightclub-is-opening-in-manchester-20190718|title=The UK's Biggest Club Night With 10,000 Capacity Is Opening In Manchester|website=pretty52.com|publisher=Pretty52}}</ref>\n\n== Parklife Festival ==\n\nLord co-created [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife Festival]] in 2010, to celebrate artists across indie, house and techno music.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> It has hosted some of the biggest names in music, including [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Liam Gallagher]] and [[Skepta]]. \n\nThe weekend festival, which moved from Platt Fields<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/parklife-festival-too-big-platt-689660|title=Festival \u2018too big\u2019 for Platt Fields|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> to Heaton Park, Manchester in 2012,<ref>http://parklifetickets.co.uk/history-of-parklife-festival/</ref> attracts 80,000 visitors each year.\n\nThe Festival employs over 4,500 people over the weekend and brings more than \u00a310million into the local economy. Each year, it raises over \u00a3100k for the Parklife Community Foundation, that is distributed to help local causes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ilovemanchester.com/how-parklife-grew-from-a-one-day-event-in-a-field-to-a-weekend-festival-bringing-in-160000-people/|title=How Parklife grew from a one day event in a field to a weekend festival bringing in 160,000 people|website=I Love MCR|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Hide Out Festival ==\n\nLord was one of the creators of Croatia\u2019s [[Hideout Festival]], a five-day alternative music extravaganza held on the island of [[Pag (island)|Pag]], Croatia, in 2011. It has sold out every single year since its conception.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=squaremile.com|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political Activity ==\n\nIn 2018, Mayor of Greater Manchester, [[Andy Burnham]], appointed Lord as Greater Manchester\u2019s first Night Time Economy Adviser, following in the footsteps of [[Amy Lam\u00e9]], who was appointed by [[Mayor of London|London Mayor]] [[Sadiq Khan]] in 2016 to be the first London night czar.\n\nUnlike Lam\u00e9, who competed with 180 people for the \u00a335,000-a-year part-time role, Lord is not paid and any income created from the role has been donated directly to charity; and did not apply for the post, although it has been established that he lobbied Burnham on the importance of nightlife before the Labour politician won the inaugural mayoral elections in May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jun/06/manchester-night-tsar-sacha-lord-all-festivals-clubs-need-drug-testing-labs|title=Manchester's night-time adviser backs drug testers for festivals and clubs|website=theguardian.com|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe role acts to advise Burnham and the [[Greater Manchester Combined Authority]] (GMCA) on all issues relating to the night-time economy, providing a voice for workers, operators and the industry as a whole.\n\nLord has since announced a raft of recommendations to improve safety, transport and cultural diversity in the region,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.morningadvertiser.co.uk/Article/2019/08/15/Manchester-night-czar-Sacha-Lord-and-mayor-Andy-Burnham-unveil-city-blueprint|title=Manchester night czar: night time venues can revive high street|website=morningadvertiser.co.uk|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> including the introduction of later opening hours for greater accessibility and the development of night-time transport links to better serve under-represented communities on the outskirts of the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/its-time-247-transport-system-16667993|title=Mayor's night tsar calls for Greater Manchester to have 24/7 transport system|first=Jennifer|last=Williams|date=July 30, 2019|website=men}}</ref>\n\nLord has also advocated for a fair wage policy for nighttime hospitality staff, including full transparency\u00a0tipping for bar and restaurant workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/8xbvzv/can-manchesters-new-night-czar-make-tipping-fair|title=Can Manchester\u2019s New Night Czar Make Tipping Fair?|website=Vice|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Lord appeared on BBC Question Time, alongside Conservative Party chairman James Cleverly, Labour\u2019s Sarah Jones, National Farmers\u2019 Union (NFU) president Minette Batters and stand-up comedian Geoff Norcott. The transmission was the last episode to be broadcast before Britain left the European Union on 31 January 2020. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000dv70/question-time-2019-30012020|title=BBC Question Time 30 01 2020|website=BBC|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nIn 2006, [[The Warehouse Project]] was found solely responsible for an increase in drug-taking in [[HM Prison Manchester|Strangeways Prison]], leading to the event being scrutinised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aah-magazine.co.uk/2018/sacha-lord-marchionne-a-glance-at-the-man-behind-warehouse-project-parklife-and-a-key-figure-in-manchesters-nightlife|title=SACHA LORD-MARCHIONNE: A GLANCE AT THE MAN BEHIND WAREHOUSE PROJECT, PARKLIFE AND A KEY FIGURE IN MANCHESTER\u2019S NIGHTLIFE|website=Aah Magazine|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> This was because the venue was right next door and the prisoners could hear the music.\n\nIn 2012, Souvik Pal, aged 18, was ejected from a Warehouse Project event on suspicion of drug use; his body was found in nearby Bridgewater Canal 22 days later.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=Square Mile|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> In 2013, Nick Bonnie, 30, collapsed at the Warehouse Project after taking almost 15 times the standard recreational dose of [[MDMA]], and subsequently died in hospital.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jun/06/manchester-night-tsar-sacha-lord-all-festivals-clubs-need-drug-testing-labs|title=Manchester's night-time adviser backs drug testers for festivals and clubs|website=The Guardian|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nLord was not directly responsible for either incident,<ref name=\"auto\"/> however, implemented drug-testing across events following the tragedies.\n\nIn 2018, Lord called for all UK clubs and festivals to have drug-testing laboratories on site,<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and implemented the testing at The Warehouse Festival, which involves confiscated drugs being tested on site, and allowing alerts to be put out warning attendees of what the drugs actually are.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n== Charitable Work ==\n\nSacha Lord is patron of the Joshua Wilson Brain Tumour Charity (charity reg number 1151518).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.joshwilson.org.uk/|title=Home &#124; The Joshua Wilson Brain Tumour Charity}}</ref>\n\nLord is also an avid campaigner on the role of mental health services for those working in the night time economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/parklife-breaks-me-sacha-lord-16039779|title='Parklife breaks me' - Sacha Lord on why night time workers need to talk about mental health|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the global Coronavirus pandemic in 2020, Lord founded the UnitedWeStream Manchester campaign<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/united-stream-goes-live-tonight-18032330|title='United We Stream goes live tonight as even more acts announced - including Hacienda night|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>, a livestream gig website which sought to raise money for the night time economy and charities in Greater Manchester through a relief fund on the website. A number of artists performed on the live stream website, including [[Roger Sanchez]] and [[Paul Oakenfold]].\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lord, Sacha}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Music festival founders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Sacha Lord\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Sacha John Edward Lord\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1972|01|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Manchester]], United Kingdom\n| nationality   = British\n| occupation    = {{Hlist|Music entrepreneur|Adviser}}\n| known_for     = {{Unbulleted list|Co-founder of [[The Warehouse Project]]|Co-founder of [[Parklife (festival)]]|Night Time Economy Adviser for [[Greater Manchester]]}}\n| website = {{URL|https://parklife.uk.com|Parklife Festival}}\n}}\n\n'''Sacha John Edward Lord''' (born 26th January 1972) is an English entrepreneur and co-creator of the [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife festival]] and [[The Warehouse Project]]. He is also the Night Time Economy Adviser for [[Greater Manchester]].\n\n== Early life ==\n\nLord was born in [[Altrincham]], Greater Manchester, and grew up in the town. His father was a textile merchant, and his mother an interior designer. Lord was educated at [[Manchester Grammar School]], leaving at aged 18 having gained two Us and an E at A-Level.  After leaving school, Lord went on to work at a clothes shop in [[Altrincham]], and later started a market stall at [[Liverpool]] market, selling leather jackets. After quitting his market job, Lord quickly found himself involved in the rave-influenced music scene, and spent most of his time listening to [[The Stone Roses]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[The Smiths]] and [[David Bowie|Bowie]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=squaremile.com|publisher=Square Mile}}</ref>\n\n== The Warehouse Project ==\n\nInspired by the success of the events, Lord launched [[the Warehouse Project]], a series of rave events running annually from September to 1 January, in 2006 with Co-Founder Sam Kandel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enforbusiness.com/interview/five-minutes-sacha-lord-marchionne-and-sam-kandel-founders-warehouse-project|title=Five minutes with... Sacha Lord-Marchionne and Sam Kandel, founders of the Warehouse Project|website=EN For Business|accessdate=1 October 2019}}}</ref>\n\nIt began operations in the disused [[Strangeways Brewery|Boddingtons Brewery]] in [[Strangeways]], and then moved into a space under [[Manchester Piccadilly railway station|Manchester Piccadilly station]], on Store Street, which previously served as an air raid shelter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djmag.com/news/detail/921|title=The Warehouse Project|website=djmag.com|publisher=DJ Mag}}</ref>\n\nThe opening night of The Warehouse Project was described by Lord as a nightmare due to its location next to the prison, and he later revealed the Governor of [[HM Prison Manchester]] had called to say it was disturbing inmates.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe Warehouse Project went onto feature some of the most in-demand names in international house and techno music, including [[New Order (band)|New Order]], [[The Chemical Brothers]] and [[Calvin Harris]] - whose appearance, Lord later went onto reveal, was a favour for an A&R at Sony. Lord revealed he put Harris ( an unknown DJ at the time) on the 21.30 slot, despite doors only opening at 22.00.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe Warehouse Project attracted 100,000 people in its first year and has continued to sell out annually.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/blogs/sacha-lord-warehouse-project-founder-appointed-manchesters-night-time-economy-adviser-future-24-hour-clubbing-2366958#CPOiVsbVBBUvryY5.99|title=Sacha Lord: the Warehouse Project founder and Manchester\u2019s Night Time Economy Adviser on the future of the city\u2019s club scene|website=NME|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Lord and Kandel moved The Warehouse Project to Depot at the former [[Manchester Mayfield railway station]] - a move which saw it become the biggest club night in the UK with a 10,000 person capacity. The move also put it on a par with the current Guinness Book of World Records holder of the largest nightclub in the world, [[Privilege Ibiza|Privilege]] in Ibiza, which can also hold 10,000 revellers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pretty52.com/news/music-the-worlds-biggest-nightclub-is-opening-in-manchester-20190718|title=The UK's Biggest Club Night With 10,000 Capacity Is Opening In Manchester|website=pretty52.com|publisher=Pretty52}}</ref>\n\n== Parklife Festival ==\n\nLord co-created [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife Festival]] in 2010, to celebrate artists across indie, house and techno music.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> It has hosted some of the biggest names in music, including [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Liam Gallagher]] and [[Skepta]]. \n\nThe weekend festival, which moved from Platt Fields<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/parklife-festival-too-big-platt-689660|title=Festival \u2018too big\u2019 for Platt Fields|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> to Heaton Park, Manchester in 2012,<ref>http://parklifetickets.co.uk/history-of-parklife-festival/</ref> attracts 80,000 visitors each year.\n\nThe Festival employs over 4,500 people over the weekend and brings more than \u00a310million into the local economy. Each year, it raises over \u00a3100k for the Parklife Community Foundation, that is distributed to help local causes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ilovemanchester.com/how-parklife-grew-from-a-one-day-event-in-a-field-to-a-weekend-festival-bringing-in-160000-people/|title=How Parklife grew from a one day event in a field to a weekend festival bringing in 160,000 people|website=I Love MCR|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Hide Out Festival ==\n\nLord was one of the creators of Croatia\u2019s [[Hideout Festival]], a five-day alternative music extravaganza held on the island of [[Pag (island)|Pag]], Croatia, in 2011. It has sold out every single year since its conception.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=squaremile.com|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political Activity ==\n\nIn 2018, Mayor of Greater Manchester, [[Andy Burnham]], appointed Lord as Greater Manchester\u2019s first Night Time Economy Adviser, following in the footsteps of [[Amy Lam\u00e9]], who was appointed by [[Mayor of London|London Mayor]] [[Sadiq Khan]] in 2016 to be the first London night czar.\n\nUnlike Lam\u00e9, who competed with 180 people for the \u00a335,000-a-year part-time role, Lord is not paid and any income created from the role has been donated directly to charity; and did not apply for the post, although it has been established that he lobbied Burnham on the importance of nightlife before the Labour politician won the inaugural mayoral elections in May 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jun/06/manchester-night-tsar-sacha-lord-all-festivals-clubs-need-drug-testing-labs|title=Manchester's night-time adviser backs drug testers for festivals and clubs|website=theguardian.com|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe role acts to advise Burnham and the [[Greater Manchester Combined Authority]] (GMCA) on all issues relating to the night-time economy, providing a voice for workers, operators and the industry as a whole.\n\nLord has since announced a raft of recommendations to improve safety, transport and cultural diversity in the region,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.morningadvertiser.co.uk/Article/2019/08/15/Manchester-night-czar-Sacha-Lord-and-mayor-Andy-Burnham-unveil-city-blueprint|title=Manchester night czar: night time venues can revive high street|website=morningadvertiser.co.uk|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> including the introduction of later opening hours for greater accessibility and the development of night-time transport links to better serve under-represented communities on the outskirts of the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/its-time-247-transport-system-16667993|title=Mayor's night tsar calls for Greater Manchester to have 24/7 transport system|first=Jennifer|last=Williams|date=July 30, 2019|website=men}}</ref>\n\nLord has also advocated for a fair wage policy for nighttime hospitality staff, including full transparency\u00a0tipping for bar and restaurant workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/8xbvzv/can-manchesters-new-night-czar-make-tipping-fair|title=Can Manchester\u2019s New Night Czar Make Tipping Fair?|website=Vice|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Lord appeared on BBC Question Time, alongside Conservative Party chairman James Cleverly, Labour\u2019s Sarah Jones, National Farmers\u2019 Union (NFU) president Minette Batters and stand-up comedian Geoff Norcott. The transmission was the last episode to be broadcast before Britain left the European Union on 31 January 2020. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/m000dv70/question-time-2019-30012020|title=BBC Question Time 30 01 2020|website=BBC|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nIn 2006, [[The Warehouse Project]] was found solely responsible for an increase in drug-taking in [[HM Prison Manchester|Strangeways Prison]], leading to the event being scrutinised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aah-magazine.co.uk/2018/sacha-lord-marchionne-a-glance-at-the-man-behind-warehouse-project-parklife-and-a-key-figure-in-manchesters-nightlife|title=SACHA LORD-MARCHIONNE: A GLANCE AT THE MAN BEHIND WAREHOUSE PROJECT, PARKLIFE AND A KEY FIGURE IN MANCHESTER\u2019S NIGHTLIFE|website=Aah Magazine|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> This was because the venue was right next door and the prisoners could hear the music.\n\nIn 2012, Souvik Pal, aged 18, was ejected from a Warehouse Project event on suspicion of drug use; his body was found in nearby Bridgewater Canal 22 days later.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://squaremile.com/features/sacha-lord-marchionne-interview|title=Sacha Lord-Marchionne interview: meet the Mancunian who changed the face of music|website=Square Mile|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> In 2013, Nick Bonnie, 30, collapsed at the Warehouse Project after taking almost 15 times the standard recreational dose of [[MDMA]], and subsequently died in hospital.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jun/06/manchester-night-tsar-sacha-lord-all-festivals-clubs-need-drug-testing-labs|title=Manchester's night-time adviser backs drug testers for festivals and clubs|website=The Guardian|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nLord was not directly responsible for either incident,<ref name=\"auto\"/> however, implemented drug-testing across events following the tragedies.\n\nIn 2018, Lord called for all UK clubs and festivals to have drug-testing laboratories on site,<ref name=\"auto1\"/> and implemented the testing at The Warehouse Festival, which involves confiscated drugs being tested on site, and allowing alerts to be put out warning attendees of what the drugs actually are.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n== Charitable Work ==\n\nSacha Lord is patron of the Joshua Wilson Brain Tumour Charity (charity reg number 1151518).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.joshwilson.org.uk/|title=Home &#124; The Joshua Wilson Brain Tumour Charity}}</ref>\n\nLord is also an avid campaigner on the role of mental health services for those working in the night time economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/parklife-breaks-me-sacha-lord-16039779|title='Parklife breaks me' - Sacha Lord on why night time workers need to talk about mental health|website=Manchester Evening News|accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lord, Sacha}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Music festival founders]]\n", "name_user": "Saw0310", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated with new information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sacha_Lord"}
{"title_page": "Chitraguptavanshi Kayastha", "text_new": "{{Italic title|string=Chitraguptavanshi}}\n{{Use Indian English|date = December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox caste\n|caste_name=Chitraguptavanshi Kayastha\n|subdivisions=12 primary sub-clans\n|populated_states=[[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Uttarakhand]], [[Delhi]], [[Punjab]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[Bihar]], [[Jharkhand]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Rajasthan]] and [[Nepal]]\n|languages=[[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Magahi language|Magahi]], [[Awadhi]]\n|religions=[[Hinduism]] and [[Historical Vedic Religion|Ancient Hinduism]]}}\n'''Chitraguptavanshi Kayastha''' ([[International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration|IAST]]: ''citraguptava\u1e43\u015b\u012b k\u0101yastha'') denotes a subgroup of the [[Kayastha]] caste of [[Hindus]] that are mainly concentrated in the [[Hindi Belt]] of [[North India]]. The functionality of the Kayasthas, who identified themselves with \"Chitragupta and paper-oriented service\", was more significant before the 1870s, and historically, their caste status have been ambiguous.<ref name=\"Bellenoit2017\">{{cite book|last=Bellenoit|first=Hayden J.|title=The Formation of the Colonial State in India: Scribes, Paper and Taxes, 1760-1860|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=9TElDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA42|year=2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-134-49429-3|p=42}}</ref>  As per the letter of council of [[Pandit]]s of Benaras to the Brahmin [[Peshwa]] Darbar regarding varna status of various Kayastha subgroups, the Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas claim their varna status as [[Brahmin]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe suffix ''vanshi'' is derived from the [[Sanskrit]] word ''vansh'' (\u0935\u0902\u0936) which translates to belonging to a particular family dynasty, as \"[[Chitragupta]]\" pertains to the Hindu god.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?tran_input=vaMza&direct=se&script=hk&link=yes&mode=3|title=\"vaMza\"|website=Spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> The word ''K\u0101yastha'' is formed from the [[Sanskrit]] ''k\u0101ya'' (body), and the suffix ''-stha'' (standing, being in).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Kayasth|title=\"Kayastha\"|website=Merriam-Webster.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Mythological origin ==\n\n==== Rig Veda ====\nRV 8.21.18 Chitra id r\u0101j\u0101 r\u0101j\u0101ka idanyake yake Saraswat\u012bmanu/ Parjanya iva tadanaddhi vristy\u0101 sahasramayut\u0101 dad\u0101t//\nChitra is king and only kinglings are the rest who dwell beside Sarasvati. He, like Parjanya with his rain, hath spread himself with thousand, yea, with myriad gifts. (Griffith 1973, reprint: 412)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=fHYnGde4BS4C&pg=PA68&lpg=PA68&dq=chitra+id+raja+rigveda&source=bl&ots=qE_jNycDIZ&sig=ACfU3U32mqIyNlaPHo_IqcXEYhHmyKOaiw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjYhv-a4-DoAhUTWX0KHYXQDcEQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=chitra%20id%20raja%20rigveda&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==== Padma Purana ====\nAccording to the earliest known writings from the ancient Hindu texts, the [[Padma Purana]], Srishthi Khand, Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas descended from the Hindu god, [[Chitragupta]], who was conceived from the body of the Hindu god, [[Brahma]], who gave [[Chitragupta]] and his descendants the duties to separate good from evil. Chitragupta was placed near Dharamaraj to register the good and evil actions of all sentient beings,that he was possessed of supernatural wisdom and became the partaker of sacrifices offered to the gods and fire.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=AH0IAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&redir_esc=y&hl=en#v=onepage&q=Srishti&f=false|title=The Kayastha Ethnology|last=Prasad|first=K.|publisher=American Methodist Mission Press|year=1877|isbn=|location=Lucknow|pages=3|chapter= PADMAPURANA, ''Srishti-Khanda''}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|reason=see talk page|date=April 2020}} According to this explanation, [[Brahma]] manifested [[Chitragupta]], a god assigned to assist [[Yama]], the god of death, in recording the deeds of humans to be judged in the afterlife. Thus the Chitraguptvanshi Kayastha are accorded a dual caste of [[Brahmin]] and [[Kshatriya]]. As per [[Puranas|Puranic]] literature, [[Chitragupta]] had two wives- Shobhavati, who was daughter of a [[Brahmin]] Susharma and Nandini who was daughter of a [[Kshatriya]] Shradhadev Manu respectively.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=ADs_AAAAIAAJ&dq=chitragupt+nandini&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%E0%A4%B6%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AD%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%80|author=Rajn\u012b K\u0101nt \u015a\u0101str\u012b|title=Hind\u016b jati k\u0101 utth\u0101n aur patan|year=1949|publisher=Kitab Mahal| quote=\u0905\u092c \u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0917\u0941\u092a\u094d\u0924 \u0915\u0947 \u0935\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0939 \u0938\u0902\u092c\u0902\u0927 \u0915\u0940 \u0935\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0924\u093e \u0938\u0941\u0928\u093f\u090f\u0964 \u0907\u0928\u0915\u0940 \u0926\u094b \u0938\u094d\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0902 \u0925\u0940\u0902-(\u0967)\u0938\u0941\u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e \u092c\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092e\u0923 \u0915\u0940 \u0915\u0928\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0936\u0941\u092d\u093e\u0935\u0924\u0940 (\u092c\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092e\u0923\u0940) \u091c\u093f\u0938\u0915\u0947 \u0906\u0920 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u0941\u090f \u0936\u094d\u0930\u094c\u0930 (\u0968)\u0936\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0926\u094d\u0927\u0926\u0947\u0935 \u092e\u0928\u0941 \u0915\u0940 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0928\u0928\u094d\u0926\u093f\u0928\u0940 (\u091a\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e) \u091c\u093f\u0938\u0915\u0947 \u091a\u093e\u0930 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u0941\u090f\u0964}}</ref> Their 12 sons represent the 12 patrilineal Chitraguptavanshi subcastes commonly recognized today.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hayden J. Bellenoit|title=The Formation of the Colonial State in India: Scribes, Paper and Taxes, 1760\u20131860|date=17 February 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-134-49429-3| quote= The north Indian Kayasthas are divided into 12 subgroups, reflecting King Chitragupta's marriage to Devi Nandini and Devi Shobhavati}}</ref> [[Kshemendra]], the 11th-century Brahmin poet from Kashmir also mentions them as decendents of Chitragupta.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=tb4NAAAAIAAJ&dq=kshemendra+%E0%A4%9A%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%97%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A4&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%E0%A4%9A%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%97%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A4+%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%B8%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A5|title=Kshemendra aura unak\u0101 sam\u0101ja|last=Chandra|first=Moti|publisher=Uttara Prade\u015ba Hind\u012b Sa\u1e43sth\u0101na|year=1984|quote= \u092f\u0947 \u0935\u093f\u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092c\u0941\u0926\u094d\u0927\u093f, \u091b\u093f\u092a\u0940 \u092c\u093e\u0924\u0947\u0902 \u0915\u0930\u0928\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0917\u0941\u092a\u094d\u0924 \u0915\u093e\u092f\u0938\u094d\u0925 \u0915\u0947\u0935\u0932 \u090f\u0915 \u0930\u0947\u0916\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u0939\u0930\u092b\u0947\u0930 \u0938\u0947 \u0938\u0939\u093f\u0924 \u0915\u094b \u0930\u0939\u093f\u0924 \u0915\u0930 \u0926\u0947\u0924\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902\u0964}}</ref>\n\n== Modern origin and social status ==\nChitraguptavanshi Kayasthas form a sub-group of the [[Kayastha]] caste of India. Following the court ruling of Patna in 1926, all [[Kayastha]]s were officially recognized as [[Dvija|twice-born]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Carroll|first=Lucy|date=February 1978|title=Colonial Perceptions of Indian Society and the Emergence of Caste(s) Associations|journal=The Journal of Asian Studies|volume=37|issue=2|pages=233\u2013250|doi=10.2307/2054164|jstor=2054164}}</ref>\n\nTheir [[dwija]] (twice-born) status has been shown by several vyavastha/council of Pandits including vyavastha of: (a) 95 pandits of Benaras dated July 21,1873 (b) pandits of Government College, Benaras in 1847 (c) 14 pandits of Oudh (d) 22 pandits of Mathura (e) 43 pandits of Jammu (f) 332 pandits of Kashmir.<ref> {{Cite book|last=Prasad|first=Kali|chapter-url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=AH0IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA19&dq=part+IV+decision+of+pandits&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj21aiFldvnAhUVA3IKHYYmBQMQ6AEIKDAA|title=The Kayastha ethnology|publisher=American Methodist Mission Press|year=1877|location=|pages=19 to 26|chapter=Part IV (iii,iv,v,vi & vii). Decision of Pandits on the nationality of Kayasthas|quote=the ancestors of Chitraguptvansi and Chandraseni Kayasthas were dwija(twice-born)...}}</ref>\n\nMarathi author TV Gupte translated the 1779 AD letter of the council of [[Pandit]]s of Benaras to the Brahmin [[Peshwa]] Darbar regarding varna status of various Kayastha subgroups which says that the Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas are [[Brahmin]].<ref>{{Cite book |section-url=https://archive.org/details/ethnographicalno00chanrich/page/n73/mode/1up |title=Ethnographical notes on Chandraseniya Kayastha Prabhu |last=Gupte |first=TV |year=1904 |page=8 |section=Appendix I.(page 7) Translation of the letter addressed by the Benaras Pandits to the Peshwa Darbar|quote=\"Kayasthas are said to be of three sorts (kinds)\u2014 (1) the Chitragupta Kayasthas (2) Dhalbhaga Gatri Kshatriya Kayasthas and (3) Kayasthas of the mixed blood. The origin of Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas is given in the Puranas. He was born from the body of Brahma while he was contemplating how he should know the good and evil acts of living beings. He was a brilliant person with pen and ink in his hands. He was known as Chitragupta and was placed near the God of death. He was appointed to record the good and evil acts of men. He was a Brahmin possessed of supra sensible knowledge. He was a god sharing the offerings at sacrifices. All the Brahmins offer him oblations of rice before taking their meals. He is called Kayastha because of his origin from the body of Brahma. Many descendants of his bearing different Gotras still exist on this earth. From this it will be seen that Kayastha Brahmins of Karhada and Khandesha are the Brahma-Kayasthas. Now about the origin of Chandraseniya Kshatriya Kayastha.....(last line) In short the will of God is all powerful Sunday, 8th Day of the white half of the Ashvin month of the year 1701(saka).\"}}</ref>\n\n== Patron deity and rituals ==\nChitraguptavanshi Kayasthas consider [[Chitragupta]] as their patron deity, one of the only few ancestral [[Tutelary deity|tutelary deities]] in Hinduism.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/chitragupta-puja-2019-know-the-significance-and-vidhi|title=Chitragupta Puja 2019|date=29 October 2019|website=Indiatoday|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[Chitragupta]] Puja is an annual festival celebrated by Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas in which ceremonial rituals involving the use of books and pens are performed for [[Chitragupta]] in order to gain blessings and good fortune for the year.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Common Sub-castes ==\nAs per [[Puranas|Puranic]] literature, [[Chitragupta]] had two wives- Devi Shobhavati, who was daughter of a [[Brahmin]] Susharma and Devi Nandini who was daughter of a [[Kshatriya]] Shradhadev Manu respectively.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=ADs_AAAAIAAJ&dq=chitragupt+nandini&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%E0%A4%B6%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AD%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%80|author=Rajn\u012b K\u0101nt \u015a\u0101str\u012b|title=Hind\u016b jati k\u0101 utth\u0101n aur patan|year=1949|publisher=Kitab Mahal| quote=\u0905\u092c \u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0917\u0941\u092a\u094d\u0924 \u0915\u0947 \u0935\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0939 \u0938\u0902\u092c\u0902\u0927 \u0915\u0940 \u0935\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0924\u093e \u0938\u0941\u0928\u093f\u090f\u0964 \u0907\u0928\u0915\u0940 \u0926\u094b \u0938\u094d\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0902 \u0925\u0940\u0902-(\u0967)\u0938\u0941\u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e \u092c\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092e\u0923 \u0915\u0940 \u0915\u0928\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0936\u0941\u092d\u093e\u0935\u0924\u0940 (\u092c\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092e\u0923\u0940) \u091c\u093f\u0938\u0915\u0947 \u0906\u0920 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u0941\u090f \u0936\u094d\u0930\u094c\u0930 (\u0968)\u0936\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0926\u094d\u0927\u0926\u0947\u0935 \u092e\u0928\u0941 \u0915\u0940 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0928\u0928\u094d\u0926\u093f\u0928\u0940 (\u091a\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e) \u091c\u093f\u0938\u0915\u0947 \u091a\u093e\u0930 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u0941\u090f\u0964}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Hayden J. Bellenoit|title=The Formation of the Colonial State in India: Scribes, Paper and Taxes, 1760\u20131860|date=17 February 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-134-49429-3| quote= The north Indian Kayasthas are divided into 12 subgroups, reflecting King Chitragupta's marriage to Devi Nandini and Devi Shobhavati}}</ref>Their 12 sons represent the 12 patrilineal Chitraguptavanshi subcastes commonly recognized today.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"FrontiersMandal\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mcvhwD5QZKEC&pg=PA175&dq=Kayastha+and+chitragupta#v=onepage&q=Kayastha%20and%20chitragupta&f=false|title=Frontiers in Migration Analysis|author=R. B. Mandal|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|year=1981|isbn=978-03-91-02471-7|page=175}}</ref> Some of these use their sub-caste's name as their surname.\n\nThese 12 sub-castes include:\n\n* [[Srivastava]] (Found mainly in [[Uttar Pradesh]])\n* Gaur or Gauda(variant of the previous spelling)(  [[Brahmins]] and [[Rajputs]] also use this surname) \n* [[Saxena]] (Found mainly in [[Uttar Pradesh]])\n* Mathur(Found mainly in [[Western Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Rajasthan]])\n* Karan(Found mainly in [[Bihar]])\n* [[Nigam]](Found mainly in [[Uttar Pradesh]])\n* [[Bhatnagar]](Found mainly in [[Western Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Rajasthan]])\n* Ambashtha(Found mainly in [[Bihar]] and [[Jharkhand]]) \n* Asthana(Found mainly in [[Uttar Pradesh]])\n* Kulshreshtha(Found mainly in [[Western Uttar Pradesh]])\n* Valmiki(Found mainly in [[Gujarat]])\n* Surajdhwaj(Found mainly in [[Eastern Uttar Pradesh]])\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Bengali Kayastha]]s\n* [[Chandraseniya Kayastha Prabhu]]\n* [[Karan Kayastha]]\n\n[[Category:Castes]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Kayastha]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title|string=Chitraguptavanshi}}\n{{Use Indian English|date = December 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox caste\n|caste_name=Chitraguptavanshi Kayastha\n|subdivisions=12 primary sub-clans\n|populated_states=[[Uttar Pradesh]], [[Uttarakhand]], [[Delhi]], [[Punjab]], [[Himachal Pradesh]], [[Bihar]], [[Jharkhand]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Rajasthan]] and [[Nepal]]\n|languages=[[Hindi language|Hindi]], [[Magahi language|Magahi]], [[Awadhi]]\n|religions=[[Hinduism]] and [[Historical Vedic Religion|Ancient Hinduism]]}}\n'''Chitraguptavanshi Kayastha''' ([[International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration|IAST]]: ''citraguptava\u1e43\u015b\u012b k\u0101yastha'') denotes a subgroup of the [[Kayastha]] caste of [[Hindus]] that are mainly concentrated in the [[Hindi Belt]] of [[North India]]. The functionality of the Kayasthas, who identified themselves with \"Chitragupta and paper-oriented service\", was more significant before the 1870s, and historically, their caste status have been ambiguous.<ref name=\"Bellenoit2017\">{{cite book|last={Bellenoit|first=Hayden J.|title=The Formation of the Colonial State in India: Scribes, Paper and Taxes, 1760-1860|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=9TElDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA42|year=2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-134-49429-3|p=42}}</ref>  As per the letter of council of [[Pandit]]s of Benaras to the Brahmin [[Peshwa]] Darbar regarding varna status of various Kayastha subgroups, the Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas claim their varna status as [[Brahmin]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe suffix ''vanshi'' is derived from the [[Sanskrit]] word ''vansh'' (\u0935\u0902\u0936) which translates to belonging to a particular family dynasty, as \"[[Chitragupta]]\" pertains to the Hindu god.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://spokensanskrit.org/index.php?tran_input=vaMza&direct=se&script=hk&link=yes&mode=3|title=\"vaMza\"|website=Spokensanskrit.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> The word ''K\u0101yastha'' is formed from the [[Sanskrit]] ''k\u0101ya'' (body), and the suffix ''-stha'' (standing, being in).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/Kayasth|title=\"Kayastha\"|website=Merriam-Webster.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Mythological origin ==\n\n==== Rig Veda ====\nRV 8.21.18 Chitra id r\u0101j\u0101 r\u0101j\u0101ka idanyake yake Saraswat\u012bmanu/ Parjanya iva tadanaddhi vristy\u0101 sahasramayut\u0101 dad\u0101t//\nChitra is king and only kinglings are the rest who dwell beside Sarasvati. He, like Parjanya with his rain, hath spread himself with thousand, yea, with myriad gifts. (Griffith 1973, reprint: 412)<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=fHYnGde4BS4C&pg=PA68&lpg=PA68&dq=chitra+id+raja+rigveda&source=bl&ots=qE_jNycDIZ&sig=ACfU3U32mqIyNlaPHo_IqcXEYhHmyKOaiw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjYhv-a4-DoAhUTWX0KHYXQDcEQ6AEwAHoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=chitra%20id%20raja%20rigveda&f=false}}</ref>\n\n==== Padma Purana ====\nAccording to the earliest known writings from the ancient Hindu texts, the [[Padma Purana]], Srishthi Khand, Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas descended from the Hindu god, [[Chitragupta]], who was conceived from the body of the Hindu god, [[Brahma]], who gave [[Chitragupta]] and his descendants the duties to separate good from evil. Chitragupta was placed near Dharamaraj to register the good and evil actions of all sentient beings,that he was possessed of supernatural wisdom and became the partaker of sacrifices offered to the gods and fire.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=AH0IAAAAQAAJ&printsec=frontcover&redir_esc=y&hl=en#v=onepage&q=Srishti&f=false|title=The Kayastha Ethnology|last=Prasad|first=K.|publisher=American Methodist Mission Press|year=1877|isbn=|location=Lucknow|pages=3|chapter= PADMAPURANA, ''Srishti-Khanda''}}</ref>{{unreliable source inline|reason=see talk page|date=April 2020}} According to this explanation, [[Brahma]] manifested [[Chitragupta]], a god assigned to assist [[Yama]], the god of death, in recording the deeds of humans to be judged in the afterlife. Thus the Chitraguptvanshi Kayastha are accorded a dual caste of [[Brahmin]] and [[Kshatriya]]. As per [[Puranas|Puranic]] literature, [[Chitragupta]] had two wives- Shobhavati, who was daughter of a [[Brahmin]] Susharma and Nandini who was daughter of a [[Kshatriya]] Shradhadev Manu respectively.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=ADs_AAAAIAAJ&dq=chitragupt+nandini&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%E0%A4%B6%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AD%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%80|author=Rajn\u012b K\u0101nt \u015a\u0101str\u012b|title=Hind\u016b jati k\u0101 utth\u0101n aur patan|year=1949|publisher=Kitab Mahal| quote=\u0905\u092c \u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0917\u0941\u092a\u094d\u0924 \u0915\u0947 \u0935\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0939 \u0938\u0902\u092c\u0902\u0927 \u0915\u0940 \u0935\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0924\u093e \u0938\u0941\u0928\u093f\u090f\u0964 \u0907\u0928\u0915\u0940 \u0926\u094b \u0938\u094d\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0902 \u0925\u0940\u0902-(\u0967)\u0938\u0941\u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e \u092c\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092e\u0923 \u0915\u0940 \u0915\u0928\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0936\u0941\u092d\u093e\u0935\u0924\u0940 (\u092c\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092e\u0923\u0940) \u091c\u093f\u0938\u0915\u0947 \u0906\u0920 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u0941\u090f \u0936\u094d\u0930\u094c\u0930 (\u0968)\u0936\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0926\u094d\u0927\u0926\u0947\u0935 \u092e\u0928\u0941 \u0915\u0940 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0928\u0928\u094d\u0926\u093f\u0928\u0940 (\u091a\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e) \u091c\u093f\u0938\u0915\u0947 \u091a\u093e\u0930 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u0941\u090f\u0964}}</ref> Their 12 sons represent the 12 patrilineal Chitraguptavanshi subcastes commonly recognized today.<ref>{{cite book|author=Hayden J. Bellenoit|title=The Formation of the Colonial State in India: Scribes, Paper and Taxes, 1760\u20131860|date=17 February 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-134-49429-3| quote= The north Indian Kayasthas are divided into 12 subgroups, reflecting King Chitragupta's marriage to Devi Nandini and Devi Shobhavati}}</ref> [[Kshemendra]], the 11th-century Brahmin poet from Kashmir also mentions them as decendents of Chitragupta.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=tb4NAAAAIAAJ&dq=kshemendra+%E0%A4%9A%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%97%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A4&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%E0%A4%9A%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%97%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A4+%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%AF%E0%A4%B8%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A5|title=Kshemendra aura unak\u0101 sam\u0101ja|last=Chandra|first=Moti|publisher=Uttara Prade\u015ba Hind\u012b Sa\u1e43sth\u0101na|year=1984|quote= \u092f\u0947 \u0935\u093f\u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092c\u0941\u0926\u094d\u0927\u093f, \u091b\u093f\u092a\u0940 \u092c\u093e\u0924\u0947\u0902 \u0915\u0930\u0928\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0917\u0941\u092a\u094d\u0924 \u0915\u093e\u092f\u0938\u094d\u0925 \u0915\u0947\u0935\u0932 \u090f\u0915 \u0930\u0947\u0916\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u0939\u0930\u092b\u0947\u0930 \u0938\u0947 \u0938\u0939\u093f\u0924 \u0915\u094b \u0930\u0939\u093f\u0924 \u0915\u0930 \u0926\u0947\u0924\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902\u0964}}</ref>\n\n== Modern origin and social status ==\nChitraguptavanshi Kayasthas form a sub-group of the [[Kayastha]] caste of India. Following the court ruling of Patna in 1926, all [[Kayastha]]s were officially recognized as [[Dvija|twice-born]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Carroll|first=Lucy|date=February 1978|title=Colonial Perceptions of Indian Society and the Emergence of Caste(s) Associations|journal=The Journal of Asian Studies|volume=37|issue=2|pages=233\u2013250|doi=10.2307/2054164|jstor=2054164}}</ref>\n\nTheir [[dwija]] (twice-born) status has been shown by several vyavastha/council of Pandits including vyavastha of: (a) 95 pandits of Benaras dated July 21,1873 (b) pandits of Government College, Benaras in 1847 (c) 14 pandits of Oudh (d) 22 pandits of Mathura (e) 43 pandits of Jammu (f) 332 pandits of Kashmir.<ref> {{Cite book|last=Prasad|first=Kali|chapter-url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=AH0IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA19&dq=part+IV+decision+of+pandits&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj21aiFldvnAhUVA3IKHYYmBQMQ6AEIKDAA|title=The Kayastha ethnology|publisher=American Methodist Mission Press|year=1877|location=|pages=19 to 26|chapter=Part IV (iii,iv,v,vi & vii). Decision of Pandits on the nationality of Kayasthas|quote=the ancestors of Chitraguptvansi and Chandraseni Kayasthas were dwija(twice-born)...}}</ref>\n\nMarathi author TV Gupte translated the 1779 AD letter of the council of [[Pandit]]s of Benaras to the Brahmin [[Peshwa]] Darbar regarding varna status of various Kayastha subgroups which says that the Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas are [[Brahmin]].<ref>{{Cite book |section-url=https://archive.org/details/ethnographicalno00chanrich/page/n73/mode/1up |title=Ethnographical notes on Chandraseniya Kayastha Prabhu |last=Gupte |first=TV |year=1904 |page=8 |section=Appendix I.(page 7) Translation of the letter addressed by the Benaras Pandits to the Peshwa Darbar|quote=\"Kayasthas are said to be of three sorts (kinds)\u2014 (1) the Chitragupta Kayasthas (2) Dhalbhaga Gatri Kshatriya Kayasthas and (3) Kayasthas of the mixed blood. The origin of Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas is given in the Puranas. He was born from the body of Brahma while he was contemplating how he should know the good and evil acts of living beings. He was a brilliant person with pen and ink in his hands. He was known as Chitragupta and was placed near the God of death. He was appointed to record the good and evil acts of men. He was a Brahmin possessed of supra sensible knowledge. He was a god sharing the offerings at sacrifices. All the Brahmins offer him oblations of rice before taking their meals. He is called Kayastha because of his origin from the body of Brahma. Many descendants of his bearing different Gotras still exist on this earth. From this it will be seen that Kayastha Brahmins of Karhada and Khandesha are the Brahma-Kayasthas. Now about the origin of Chandraseniya Kshatriya Kayastha.....(last line) In short the will of God is all powerful Sunday, 8th Day of the white half of the Ashvin month of the year 1701(saka).\"}}</ref>\n\n== Patron deity and rituals ==\nChitraguptavanshi Kayasthas consider [[Chitragupta]] as their patron deity, one of the only few ancestral [[Tutelary deity|tutelary deities]] in Hinduism.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/chitragupta-puja-2019-know-the-significance-and-vidhi|title=Chitragupta Puja 2019|date=29 October 2019|website=Indiatoday|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[Chitragupta]] Puja is an annual festival celebrated by Chitraguptavanshi Kayasthas in which ceremonial rituals involving the use of books and pens are performed for [[Chitragupta]] in order to gain blessings and good fortune for the year.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Common Sub-castes ==\nAs per [[Puranas|Puranic]] literature, [[Chitragupta]] had two wives- Devi Shobhavati, who was daughter of a [[Brahmin]] Susharma and Devi Nandini who was daughter of a [[Kshatriya]] Shradhadev Manu respectively.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=ADs_AAAAIAAJ&dq=chitragupt+nandini&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%E0%A4%B6%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%AD%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B5%E0%A4%A4%E0%A5%80|author=Rajn\u012b K\u0101nt \u015a\u0101str\u012b|title=Hind\u016b jati k\u0101 utth\u0101n aur patan|year=1949|publisher=Kitab Mahal| quote=\u0905\u092c \u091a\u093f\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0917\u0941\u092a\u094d\u0924 \u0915\u0947 \u0935\u093f\u0935\u093e\u0939 \u0938\u0902\u092c\u0902\u0927 \u0915\u0940 \u0935\u093e\u0930\u094d\u0924\u093e \u0938\u0941\u0928\u093f\u090f\u0964 \u0907\u0928\u0915\u0940 \u0926\u094b \u0938\u094d\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e\u0902 \u0925\u0940\u0902-(\u0967)\u0938\u0941\u0936\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e \u092c\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092e\u0923 \u0915\u0940 \u0915\u0928\u094d\u092f\u093e \u0936\u0941\u092d\u093e\u0935\u0924\u0940 (\u092c\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092e\u0923\u0940) \u091c\u093f\u0938\u0915\u0947 \u0906\u0920 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u0941\u090f \u0936\u094d\u0930\u094c\u0930 (\u0968)\u0936\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0926\u094d\u0927\u0926\u0947\u0935 \u092e\u0928\u0941 \u0915\u0940 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0928\u0928\u094d\u0926\u093f\u0928\u0940 (\u091a\u0924\u094d\u0930\u093f\u092f\u093e) \u091c\u093f\u0938\u0915\u0947 \u091a\u093e\u0930 \u092a\u0941\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0939\u0941\u090f\u0964}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Hayden J. Bellenoit|title=The Formation of the Colonial State in India: Scribes, Paper and Taxes, 1760\u20131860|date=17 February 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-134-49429-3| quote= The north Indian Kayasthas are divided into 12 subgroups, reflecting King Chitragupta's marriage to Devi Nandini and Devi Shobhavati}}</ref>Their 12 sons represent the 12 patrilineal Chitraguptavanshi subcastes commonly recognized today.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"FrontiersMandal\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=mcvhwD5QZKEC&pg=PA175&dq=Kayastha+and+chitragupta#v=onepage&q=Kayastha%20and%20chitragupta&f=false|title=Frontiers in Migration Analysis|author=R. B. Mandal|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|year=1981|isbn=978-03-91-02471-7|page=175}}</ref> Some of these use their sub-caste's name as their surname.\n\nThese 12 sub-castes include:\n\n* [[Srivastava]] (Found mainly in [[Uttar Pradesh]])\n* Gaur or Gauda(variant of the previous spelling)(  [[Brahmins]] and [[Rajputs]] also use this surname) \n* [[Saxena]] (Found mainly in [[Uttar Pradesh]])\n* Mathur(Found mainly in [[Western Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Rajasthan]])\n* Karan(Found mainly in [[Bihar]])\n* [[Nigam]](Found mainly in [[Uttar Pradesh]])\n* [[Bhatnagar]](Found mainly in [[Western Uttar Pradesh]] and [[Rajasthan]])\n* Ambashtha(Found mainly in [[Bihar]] and [[Jharkhand]]) \n* Asthana(Found mainly in [[Uttar Pradesh]])\n* Kulshreshtha(Found mainly in [[Western Uttar Pradesh]])\n* Valmiki(Found mainly in [[Gujarat]])\n* Surajdhwaj(Found mainly in [[Eastern Uttar Pradesh]])\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Bengali Kayastha]]s\n* [[Chandraseniya Kayastha Prabhu]]\n* [[Karan Kayastha]]\n\n[[Category:Castes]]\n[[Category:Hindu communities]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Kayastha]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups]]\n", "name_user": "Ekdalian", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chitraguptavanshi_Kayastha"}
{"title_page": "NS Daures", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=NS ''Daures''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Namibian Navy Type 037 Class boats.jpg\n|Ship caption=NS ''Daures'' in the foreground\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=Namibia\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Namibia|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Daures''\n|Ship namesake=[[Daures]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=  \n|Ship recommissioned= 27 October 2017\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage= \n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=[[Walvis Bay]]\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status={{Ship in active service}}\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption= \n|Ship class=Haiqing-class patrol boat\n|Ship displacement= {{Convert|478|t|LT|0}}\n|Ship length={{Convert|62.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{Convert|7.2|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught={{Convert|2.4|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship power=* 4 \u00d7 Chinese PR 230ZC [[diesel engine]]s \n* {{Convert|4000|hp|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion= 4 shafts\n|Ship speed={{Convert|28|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{Convert|1300|nmi|km|abbr=on|lk=in}} at {{Convert|15|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}\n|Ship endurance= \n|Ship boats=2 [[Rigid-hulled inflatable boat]]s\n|Ship complement=71\n|Ship sensors= * 1 \u00d7 Type 723 surface search radar\n* Chinese copy of French Thomson-Sintra medium frequency SS-12 VDS sonar\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=* 2 \u00d7  37 mm gun (2 \u00d7 1)\n* 2 \u00d7 Type 69 14.5 mm heavy machine guns (2 \u00d7 2)\n* 2 \u00d7 Type 87 6-tubed ASW mortar  \n|Ship armour=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''NS ''Daures'' (C12)''' is a [[patrol boat]] of the [[Namibian Navy]] and [[sister ship]] of {{ship|NS|Brukkaros}}. Formerly a [[People's Liberation Army Navy]] [[Type 037 corvette#Type 037I Haiqing-class submarine chaser|Haiqing-class submarine chaser]], it was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] on 27 October 2017 into the Namibian Navy. The vessel is used to patrol Namibia's [[exclusive economic zone]].\n\n==Description==\nThe Haiqing class are a follow-on class of [[submarine chaser]]s to the preceding [[Type 037 corvette#Type 037I Haiqing-class submarine chaser|Type 037 submarine chasers]] of the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]]. The ship is armed with two 6-tubed anti-submarine mortar launchers. It is also armed with two 37 mm guns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://economist.com.na/30035/wheels-wings/two-chinese-built-naval-vessels-commissioned-in-walvis-bay/ |title=Two Chinese-Built Naval Vessels Commissioned in Walvis Bay |work=Namibia Economist |date=30 October 2017 |accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Operational history==\nThe boat was previously a PLA Navy ship. In 2014 the [[China|Chinese]] government offered to donate it to the Namibian Navy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbc.na/new-ships |title=President Hage Geingob commissions two naval ships |work=nbc.na |date=27 October 2017 |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref> The patrol boat was then refurbished by Poly Technologies<ref name=defenceweb>{{cite web |url=http://www.defenceweb.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=49787&catid=74&Itemid=30 |title=Namibia commissions two naval vessels |work=defenceweb.co.za |date=7 November 2017 |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref> after which Namibian crews went to China for training on the ship. The ship was then sent to Namibia on the deck of the cargo ship ''Da Qing'' and arrived in Namibia on 9 July 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://namibtimes.net/two-new-navy-vessels-delivered-for-namibia/ |title=Two New Navy Vessels Delivered for Namibia |work=Namib Times |date=7 November 2017 |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe ship is named after [[Daures Constituency]] in [[Erongo Region]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newera.com.na/2017/10/30/two-navy-patrol-vessels-commissioned/ |title=Two navy patrol vessels commissioned |work=newera.com |date=30 October 2017 |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref> and was [[Ship commissioning|commissioned]] into the Namibian Navy on 27 October 2017.by President [[Hage Geingob]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.erongo.com.na/news/president-commissions-navy-patrol-vessels-2017-11-03 |title=President commissions navy patrol vessels |work=erongo.com.na |date=3 November 2017 |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref> The ship is operationally utilised for general [[exclusive economic zone]] management.<ref name=defenceweb/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/article/75328/namibian-navy-commissions-sub-chasers |title=Namibian Navy commissions 'sub chasers' |work=janes.com |url-status=dead |date=31 October 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802163031/https://www.janes.com/article/75328/namibian-navy-commissions-sub-chasers |archivedate=2 August 2018 |accessdate=31 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daures (C12)}}\n[[Category:Ships of the Namibian Navy]]\n[[Category:Military of Namibia]]\n[[Category:2010s ships]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=NS ''Daures''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Namibian Navy Type 037 Class boats.jpg\n|Ship caption=NS ''Daures'' in the foreground\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=Namibia\n|Ship flag={{shipboxflag|Namibia|naval}}\n|Ship name=''Daures''\n|Ship namesake=[[Daures]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=  \n|Shi