{"title_page": "IMSciences", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name         = Institute of Management Sciences\n|image_name      = File:IMSciences_Logo.jpg\n|image_size      = 175px\n|motto        = Management Education with Public Spirit and Market Dynamism\n|established     = {{Start date|1995}}\n|type         = [[Public university|Public]]\n|endowment    = Rs. 42m<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=106&Itemid=70|title=Funding grants for research and development|publisher=IMSciences|accessdate=18 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801140340/http://imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=106&Itemid=70|archivedate=1 August 2012}}</ref>\n|staff        =\n|faculty      =\n|chancellor   =\n|director     = Dr. M. Mohsin Khan\n|students     = 3000+\n|undergrad    =\n|postgrad     =\n|free_label      = Acronym\n|free            = IM Sciences\n|city         = [[Peshawar]]\n|country      = [[Pakistan]]\n|affiliations    = [[National Business Education Accreditation Council |NBEAC]], [[National Computing Education Accreditation Council |NCEAC]], [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]]\n|website      = [http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/ www.imsciences.edu.pk]\n}}\n\nThe '''Institute of Management Sciences''' (also known as '''IMSciences''') is a degree-granting institution located in [[Peshawar]], [[Pakistan]]. A [[Public university|public]], Institute of Management Sciences is a Public sector Government owned autonomous institution recognized by Higher Education Commission Islamabad and working under NWFP Ordinance No. XXXVII of 2002, the institute was founded in 1995 from elements of the [[University of Peshawar]]. It is ranked at 3rd in the Business Category by [[Higher Education Commission of Pakistan]] <ref name=\"History\">{{cite web | url=http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=47&Itemid=55 | title=IMSciences History | publisher=IMSciences | accessdate=December 1, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025024814/http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=47&Itemid=55 | archivedate=October 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe institute is located in the [[Hayatabad]] area of [[Peshawar]] and is organised into four faculties - management sciences, computer sciences, information technology and liberal arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=101&Itemid=69|title=Faculties|publisher=IMSciences|accessdate=18 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809022031/http://imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=101&Itemid=69|archivedate=9 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt is recognised as a degree-awarding institution by the [[Higher Education Commission of Pakistan]] and is chartered by the [[Government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Government of Khyber Pakhtoonkhwa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hec.gov.pk/ourinstitutes/pages/default.aspx |title=HEC recognized Universities/Degree Awarding Institutes (DAIs) of Pakistan in Public & Private Sector as on September 2011 |publisher=[[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|Higher Education Commission]] |location=Pakistan |date=September 2011 |accessdate=11 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200812/http://www.hec.gov.pk/ourinstitutes/pages/default.aspx |archivedate=29 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe institute has two incubation centers named, '''IM|Durshal''' which is a combined program of KPITB and IM|Sciences, and '''Business Incubation Centre (BIC)'''.\n\n==Degrees offered==\n\nThe institute has been granting degrees since 2005, including in the following fields:<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web | url=http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=119 | title=About the Institute | publisher=IMSciences | accessdate=December 1, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025030700/http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=119 | archivedate=October 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n* Management\n* Computer Science and Information Technology\n* Data Science and Software Engineering \n* Planning and Policy Analysis\n* Banking\n* Finance and Accounting\n* Marketing\n* Health Service and Hospital Management\n* Local Government and Public Enterprises\n* Applied Economics\n* Social Sciences\n* English (Literature & Linguistics)\n\nThe Institute also offers a \"split site PhD\" program with the Southampton Management School at the [[University of Southampton]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/management/news/2011/05/09_international_links.page | title=International links recognised | publisher=Southampton Management School | date=May 9, 2011 | accessdate=December 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url = http://online-phd-uk.co.uk/online-phd-uk-university-of-southampton-split-site-phd/|title = University of Southampton-Split-Site PhD|year = 2015|accessdate = February 15, 2015|website = Online PhD Degree Programs}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Khyber Pakhtunkhwa}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1955]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Peshawar]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Hayatabad]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name         = Institute of Management Sciences\n|image_name      = File:IMSciences_Logo.jpg\n|image_size      = 175px\n|motto        = Management Education with Public Spirit and Market Dynamism\n|established     = {{Start date|1995}}\n|type         = [[Public university|Public]]\n|endowment    = Rs. 42m<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=106&Itemid=70|title=Funding grants for research and development|publisher=IMSciences|accessdate=18 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120801140340/http://imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=106&Itemid=70|archivedate=1 August 2012}}</ref>\n|staff        =\n|faculty      =\n|chancellor   =\n|director     = Dr. M. Mohsin Khan\n|students     = 3000+\n|undergrad    =\n|postgrad     =\n|free_label      = Acronym\n|free            = IM Sciences\n|city         = [[Peshawar]]\n|country      = [[Pakistan]]\n|affiliations    = [[National Business Education Accreditation Council |NBEAC]], [[National Computing Education Accreditation Council |NCEAC]], [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|HEC]]\n|website      = [http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/ www.imsciences.edu.pk]\n}}\n\nThe '''Institute of Management Sciences''' (also known as '''IMSciences''') is a degree-granting institution located in [[Peshawar]], [[Pakistan]]. A [[Public university|public]], Institute of Management Sciences is a Public sector Government owned autonomous institution recognized by Higher Education Commission Islamabad and working under NWFP Ordinance No. XXXVII of 2002, the institute was founded in 1995 from elements of the [[University of Peshawar]]. It is ranked at 4th in the Business Category by [[Higher Education Commission of Pakistan]] <ref name=\"History\">{{cite web | url=http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=47&Itemid=55 | title=IMSciences History | publisher=IMSciences | accessdate=December 1, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025024814/http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=47&Itemid=55 | archivedate=October 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe institute is located in the [[Hayatabad]] area of [[Peshawar]] and is organised into four faculties - management sciences, computer sciences, information technology and liberal arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=101&Itemid=69|title=Faculties|publisher=IMSciences|accessdate=18 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120809022031/http://imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=101&Itemid=69|archivedate=9 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt is recognised as a degree-awarding institution by the [[Higher Education Commission of Pakistan]] and is chartered by the [[Government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Government of Khyber Pakhtoonkhwa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hec.gov.pk/ourinstitutes/pages/default.aspx |title=HEC recognized Universities/Degree Awarding Institutes (DAIs) of Pakistan in Public & Private Sector as on September 2011 |publisher=[[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)|Higher Education Commission]] |location=Pakistan |date=September 2011 |accessdate=11 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200812/http://www.hec.gov.pk/ourinstitutes/pages/default.aspx |archivedate=29 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe institute has two incubation centers named, '''IM|Durshal''' which is a combined program of KPITB and IM|Sciences, and '''Business Incubation Centre (BIC)'''.\n\n==Degrees offered==\n\nThe institute has been granting degrees since 2005, including in the following fields:<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web | url=http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=119 | title=About the Institute | publisher=IMSciences | accessdate=December 1, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025030700/http://www.imsciences.edu.pk/imweb/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=119 | archivedate=October 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n* Management\n* Computer Science and Information Technology\n* Data Science and Software Engineering \n* Planning and Policy Analysis\n* Banking\n* Finance and Accounting\n* Marketing\n* Health Service and Hospital Management\n* Local Government and Public Enterprises\n* Applied Economics\n* Social Sciences\n* English (Literature & Linguistics)\n\nThe Institute also offers a \"split site PhD\" program with the Southampton Management School at the [[University of Southampton]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/management/news/2011/05/09_international_links.page | title=International links recognised | publisher=Southampton Management School | date=May 9, 2011 | accessdate=December 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url = http://online-phd-uk.co.uk/online-phd-uk-university-of-southampton-split-site-phd/|title = University of Southampton-Split-Site PhD|year = 2015|accessdate = February 15, 2015|website = Online PhD Degree Programs}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Khyber Pakhtunkhwa}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1955]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Peshawar]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Hayatabad]]\n", "name_user": "Maaz Jan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IMSciences"}
{"title_page": "Crossing-based interface", "text_new": "'''Crossing-based interfaces''' are [[graphical user interface]]s that use crossing gestures instead of, or in complement to, [[point-and-click|pointing]].\n\n==Goal-crossing tasks==\n\nA '''pointing task''' involves moving a cursor inside a graphical object and pressing a button, whereas a '''goal-crossing task''' involves moving a cursor beyond a boundary of a targeted graphical object.\n \nGoal crossing has been little investigated, despite sometimes being used on today's interfaces (e.g., mouse-over effects, hierarchical menus navigation, auto-retractable taskbars and [[cursor hotspot|hot corners]]). Still, several advantages of crossing over pointing have been identified:\n\n* Elongated objects such as [[hyperlinks]] are faster to cross than to point.\n* Several objects can be crossed at the same time within the same [[mouse gesture|gesture]].\n* Crossing allows triggering actions when buttons are not available (e.g., while an object is being [[drag-and-drop|dragged]]).\n* Crossing-based [[GUI widget|widgets]] can be designed to be more compact than pointing-based ones. This may be useful for small display devices.\n* Goal crossing is particularly natural on [[Stylus (computing)|stylus]]-based devices. On these devices, crossing an object back and forth is easier than [[double-clicking]].\n* Crossing can be a good alternative for users who have difficulties with clicking or double-clicking.\n\nThere are several other ways of triggering actions in user interfaces, either graphic ([[mouse gesture|gestures]]) and non-graphic ([[keyboard shortcuts]], [[speech recognition|speech commands]]). Anirudh Anirudh pratap singh baghel \n\n==Laws of crossing==\n\nVariants of [[Fitts' law]] have been described for goal-crossing tasks (Accot and Zhai 2002). Fitts' law is seen as a ''Law of pointing'', describing variability in the direction of the pointer's movement. The ''Law of crossing'' describes the allowed variability in the direction perpendicular to movement, and the [[steering law]] describes movement along a tunnel.\n\n==References==\n\n* Original work\n** Accot, J. and Zhai, S. (2002). More than dotting the i's - foundations for crossing-based interfaces, in Proc. of CHI'2002: ACM Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems, Minneapolis, Minnesota, April 2002. pp 73-80.\n* Selected subsequent work\n** Apitz, G. and Guimbreti\u00e8re F. (2004). CrossY: a crossing-based drawing application. In Proceedings of the 17th Annual ACM Symposium on User interface Software and Technology (Santa Fe, NM, USA, October 24 - 27, 2004). UIST '04. ACM Press, New York, NY, 3-12.\n** Dragicevic, P. (2004). Combining crossing-based and paper-based interaction paradigms for dragging and dropping between overlapping windows. In Proceedings of the 17th Annual ACM Symposium on User interface Software and Technology (Santa Fe, NM, USA, October 24 - 27, 2004). UIST '04. ACM Press, New York, NY, 193-196.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Fitts Law]] &mdash; A principle of human movement which predicts the time required to move from a starting position to a final target area.\n* [[Accot-Zhai steering law]] &mdash; An extension of Fitt's law to ''steering'' tasks.\n* [[Interaction technique]]\n* [[Pie menu]]\n\n==External links==\n\n*[http://www.almaden.ibm.com/u/zhai/topics/LawsOfAction.htm Laws of Action] by Shumin Zhai\n*[http://www.cs.umd.edu/hcil/crossy/ CrossY] interface by Apitz and Guimbreti\u00e8re\n*[http://www.dgp.toronto.edu/~dragice/foldndrop/ Dragicevic's Fold'n'Drop technique]\n*[http://www.dontclick.it/ Don't Click It] - A clickless proof-of-concept interface\n\n[[Category:User interface techniques]]\n", "text_old": "'''Crossing-based interfaces''' are [[graphical user interface]]s that use crossing gestures instead of, or in complement to, [[point-and-click|pointing]].\n\n==Goal-crossing tasks==\n\nA '''pointing task''' involves moving a cursor inside a graphical object and pressing a button, whereas a '''goal-crossing task''' involves moving a cursor beyond a boundary of a targeted graphical object.\n \nGoal crossing has been little investigated, despite sometimes being used on today's interfaces (e.g., mouse-over effects, hierarchical menus navigation, auto-retractable taskbars and [[cursor hotspot|hot corners]]). Still, several advantages of crossing over pointing have been identified:\n\n* Elongated objects such as [[hyperlinks]] are faster to cross than to point.\n* Several objects can be crossed at the same time within the same [[mouse gesture|gesture]].\n* Crossing allows triggering actions when buttons are not available (e.g., while an object is being [[drag-and-drop|dragged]]).\n* Crossing-based [[GUI widget|widgets]] can be designed to be more compact than pointing-based ones. This may be useful for small display devices.\n* Goal crossing is particularly natural on [[Stylus (computing)|stylus]]-based devices. On these devices, crossing an object back and forth is easier than [[double-clicking]].\n* Crossing can be a good alternative for users who have difficulties with clicking or double-clicking.\n\nThere are several other ways of triggering actions in user interfaces, either graphic ([[mouse gesture|gestures]]) and non-graphic ([[keyboard shortcuts]], [[speech recognition|speech commands]]).\n\n==Laws of crossing==\n\nVariants of [[Fitts' law]] have been described for goal-crossing tasks (Accot and Zhai 2002). Fitts' law is seen as a ''Law of pointing'', describing variability in the direction of the pointer's movement. The ''Law of crossing'' describes the allowed variability in the direction perpendicular to movement, and the [[steering law]] describes movement along a tunnel.\n\n==References==\n\n* Original work\n** Accot, J. and Zhai, S. (2002). More than dotting the i's - foundations for crossing-based interfaces, in Proc. of CHI'2002: ACM Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems, Minneapolis, Minnesota, April 2002. pp 73-80.\n* Selected subsequent work\n** Apitz, G. and Guimbreti\u00e8re F. (2004). CrossY: a crossing-based drawing application. In Proceedings of the 17th Annual ACM Symposium on User interface Software and Technology (Santa Fe, NM, USA, October 24 - 27, 2004). UIST '04. ACM Press, New York, NY, 3-12.\n** Dragicevic, P. (2004). Combining crossing-based and paper-based interaction paradigms for dragging and dropping between overlapping windows. In Proceedings of the 17th Annual ACM Symposium on User interface Software and Technology (Santa Fe, NM, USA, October 24 - 27, 2004). UIST '04. ACM Press, New York, NY, 193-196.\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Fitts Law]] &mdash; A principle of human movement which predicts the time required to move from a starting position to a final target area.\n* [[Accot-Zhai steering law]] &mdash; An extension of Fitt's law to ''steering'' tasks.\n* [[Interaction technique]]\n* [[Pie menu]]\n\n==External links==\n\n*[http://www.almaden.ibm.com/u/zhai/topics/LawsOfAction.htm Laws of Action] by Shumin Zhai\n*[http://www.cs.umd.edu/hcil/crossy/ CrossY] interface by Apitz and Guimbreti\u00e8re\n*[http://www.dgp.toronto.edu/~dragice/foldndrop/ Dragicevic's Fold'n'Drop technique]\n*[http://www.dontclick.it/ Don't Click It] - A clickless proof-of-concept interface\n\n[[Category:User interface techniques]]\n", "name_user": "Anirudh pratap singh baghel", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crossing-based_interface"}
{"title_page": "Addison Rae", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|American social media personality}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Addison Rae\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Addison Rae Easterling\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|2000|10|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lafayette, Louisiana]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Internet celebrity|Social media personality]]|Dancer}}\n| years_active       = 2019\u2013present\n| known_for          = [[TikTok]]\n| relatives          = Alex Geelmuyden \n}}\n\n'''Addison Rae Easterling''' (born October 6, 2000), colloquially known as '''Addison Rae''', is an [[United States|American]] [[Internet celebrity|social media personality]] and dancer. As of April 2020, she has accumulated 1.5 billion likes and 33 million followers on the social video sharing app [[TikTok]], being the [[List of most-followed TikTok accounts|6th most-followed individual on the platform]]. \n\n==Biography==\nAddison Rae Easterling was born on October 6, 2000, in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]], to Monty Lopez and Sheri Easterling<ref name=\"seven\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/a31823306/who-is-addison-rae-easterling/ |title=Everything You Need to Know About TikTok Star Addison Rae |last=Kim |first=Yerin |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}} </ref>. She also has two brothers named Enzo and Lucas.<ref name=\"seven\" /> She grew up in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]]. She attended [[Louisiana State University]], in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]. Before moving to Los Angeles to pursue TikTok, the dancer attended [[Calvary Baptist Academy (Shreveport, Louisiana)|Calvary Baptist Academy]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]].<ref name=\"sbmag\">{{cite web |url=https://sbmag.net/sb-art-junior-addison-easterling-calvary-baptist-academy/ |title=SB Art Junior: Addison Easterling, Calvary Baptist Academy |date=March 2019 |website=SB Mag |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe joined the TikTok platform in July of 2019.<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/katetalbot/2020/04/07/meet-addison-rae-one-of-tiktoks-biggest-stars/#4f515fa671ed |title=Meet Addison Rae, One Of TikTok\u2019s Biggest Stars |last=Talbot |first=Kate |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She has been part of the TikTok collaborative group [[The Hype House]] along with 18 others, including [[Charli D'Amelio]] and Dixie D'Amelio.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/style/hype-house-los-angeles-tik-tok.html |title=Hype House and the Los Angeles TikTok Mansion Gold Rush |last=Lorenz |first=Taylor |date=January 3, 2020 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Easterling signed with talent agency [[Endeavor (company)|WME]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tiktoker-addison-rae-signs-wme-1271521 |title=TikToker Addison Rae Signs With WME (Exclusive) |last=Jarvey |first=Natalie |date=January 21, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{TikTok}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n* {{IMDb name}} \n* {{Twitter}}\n\nhttps://www.instagram.com/alexksxx/?hl=nb\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rae, Addison}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dancers]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Female TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lafayette, Louisiana]]\n__INDEX__\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Short description|American social media personality}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Addison Rae\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Addison Rae Easterling\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|2000|10|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lafayette, Louisiana]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Internet celebrity|Social media personality]]|Dancer}}\n| years_active       = 2019\u2013present\n| known_for          = [[TikTok]]\n| relatives          = Alex Geelmuyden \n}}\n\n'''Addison Rae Easterling''' (born October 6, 2000), colloquially known as '''Addison Rae''', is an [[United States|American]] [[Internet celebrity|social media personality]] and dancer. As of April 2020, she has accumulated 1.5 billion likes and 33 million followers on the social video sharing app [[TikTok]], being the [[List of most-followed TikTok accounts|6th most-followed individual on the platform]].\n\n==Biography==\nAddison Rae Easterling was born on October 6, 2000, in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]], to Monty Lopez and Sheri Easterling<ref name=\"seven\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/a31823306/who-is-addison-rae-easterling/ |title=Everything You Need to Know About TikTok Star Addison Rae |last=Kim |first=Yerin |date=March 20, 2020 |website=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}} </ref>. She also has two brothers named Enzo and Lucas.<ref name=\"seven\" /> She grew up in [[Lafayette, Louisiana]]. She attended [[Louisiana State University]], in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]. Before moving to Los Angeles to pursue TikTok, the dancer attended [[Calvary Baptist Academy (Shreveport, Louisiana)|Calvary Baptist Academy]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]].<ref name=\"sbmag\">{{cite web |url=https://sbmag.net/sb-art-junior-addison-easterling-calvary-baptist-academy/ |title=SB Art Junior: Addison Easterling, Calvary Baptist Academy |date=March 2019 |website=SB Mag |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe joined the TikTok platform in July of 2019.<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/katetalbot/2020/04/07/meet-addison-rae-one-of-tiktoks-biggest-stars/#4f515fa671ed |title=Meet Addison Rae, One Of TikTok\u2019s Biggest Stars |last=Talbot |first=Kate |date=April 7, 2020 |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> She has been part of the TikTok collaborative group [[The Hype House]] along with 18 others, including [[Charli D'Amelio]] and Dixie D'Amelio.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/03/style/hype-house-los-angeles-tik-tok.html |title=Hype House and the Los Angeles TikTok Mansion Gold Rush |last=Lorenz |first=Taylor |date=January 3, 2020 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Easterling signed with talent agency [[Endeavor (company)|WME]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tiktoker-addison-rae-signs-wme-1271521 |title=TikToker Addison Rae Signs With WME (Exclusive) |last=Jarvey |first=Natalie |date=January 21, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{TikTok}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n* {{IMDb name}} \n* {{Twitter}}\n\nhttps://www.instagram.com/alexksxx/?hl=nb\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rae, Addison}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American dancers]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Female TikTokers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lafayette, Louisiana]]\n", "name_user": "Gabbiloi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addison_Rae"}
